[] a def:Item ;
    dh:slug "dataset-structure" ;
    dct:title "Dataset structure" ;
    dct:description "Learn what RDF dataset structure is supported by LinkedDataHub" ;
    sioc:content """<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    <p class="lead">Here we describe the RDF dataset structures supported by LinkedDataHub.</p>
    <p>URIs relative to the application base URI</p>
    <div>
        <h2 id="generic">Generic</h2>
        <p>Any RDF dataset is supported in this mode. It can contain data in the default graph, named
            graphs, or a combination of those. The write operations are supported using
            SPARQL <a href="administration/sitemap/#commands">update commands</a>.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
        <h2 id="linked-data-hub">LinkedDataHub</h2>
        <p>Default LinkedDataHub dataset structure follows these conventions:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>the default graph is not used</li>
            <li>each document is stored using 2 named graphs: the <dfn>content graph</dfn> with the
                RDF properties and content that the user can update; and the <dfn>meta-graph</dfn> with
              system metadata</li>
            <li>an inverse functional relationship exists between the document and its content graph,
                as well as the content graph and the meta graph. That allows to locate the graph
                with the document description using the <code>void:inDataset</code> document property,
                which can be managed using the <a href="http-api#graphs">Graph Store Protocol</a> in
                order to change the description(s) of the document or its related resources.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The LinkedDataHub dataset can be <a href="manage-apps">installed</a> into an application service
            by the application's owners.</p>
    </div>
    <p>The distinction between dataset structures matters mostly for updates and versioning. It is much
        more straight-forward to change graph contents using GSP than update resource description using
        SPARQL.</p>
</div>"""^^rdf:XMLLiteral .